3.2 Positional

I created an algorithm to determine whether a song was in a similar position on the Top 100 list of two different countries. I then compared every country to every other country.

In order to compare the position of each country I filtered the data set to segment the data by country and then used the map_df function to iterate over the list and compare the position of songs. I then counted the number of matches in the list. This data could then be plotted using ggPlot2.

3.3 List-Wide

I created an algorithm to determine whether a song was in the Top 100 list of two different countries. I then compared every country to every other country.

In order to conduct the list-wide analysis I needed to iterate over each list and compare it to the songs in every other list and then count the matches. It is worthwhile to note here that as with the positional data set it was important that I was conducting this analysis efficiently as there were a significant number of comparisons to be made as such I wrote an algorithm with would sample without replacement to ensure that I wasnt doing comparisons more than once. This data could then be plotted using ggPlot2.

Creating the vulgarity comparison was much more straightforward than the positional and list-wide comparisons as it simply required me to filter by the listed country and then count the number of explicit tracks which I then displayed using the summarise function. 4. Final Reflection

4.1 General Reflection

One important idea that I have learnt from module 5 is how we can scrape data. Sometimes we do not have traditional data collection tools (e.g surveys, studies) available to us nor a preexisting dataset, web scraping is an effective way in which to curate existing data. There are a number of important considerations when web-scraping, including; attempting to scrape elements which are unlikely to change to ensure your scraping is robust and less likely to be effected by changes to the website and secondly ensuring that you are scraping data ethnically, this means by complying with the terms of service of the website (and the robot.txt file) and not overloading the website with requests.

While this course has covered a substantial breadth of content, I think that the most important thing I have learnt is how to manipulate data in such a way that I can draw insights from that data. This includes everything from filtering and sub-setting data to mutating columns to joining tables together to draw insights from a larger pool of data.

I am particularly interested how we can further automate the data-collection process particularly in the context of web-scraping. I am additionally interested how I can protect my own data on my websites from being scraped when I do not want it to be.

5. Code Appendix

5.1 Web-scraping

library(tidyverse)
library(rvest)

urls = read.csv("top100s.csv")

apple_data = map_df(1 : length(urls$Country), function(i) {
  Sys.sleep(2)
  
  url = urls$URL[i]
  page = read_html(url)
  
  trackId=page %>%
    html_elements(".songs-list") %>%
    html_elements("a") %>%
    html_attr("href") %>%
    .[str_detect(., "/song/")] %>%
    str_remove_all("https://music.apple.com/us/song/")
  
  scrapedTrackName = page %>%
    html_elements(".songs-list-row__song-name") %>%
    html_text2()
  
  trackRank = page %>%
    html_elements(".songs-list-row__rank") %>%
    html_text2()
  
  return(tibble(trackId, trackRank, scrapedTrackName, urls$Country[i], Sys.Date()))
})

apple_data = rename(apple_data, rankedCountry = 4, dateRetrived = 5)

saveRDS(apple_data, "apple_data.rds")

5.2 API Call

library(tidyverse)
library(jsonlite)

apple_data = readRDS("apple_data.rds")

trackIds <- apple_data$trackId %>%
  unique() %>%
  na.omit()

itunes_data = map_df(1 : length(trackIds), function(i){
  Sys.sleep(2)
  
  song_id <- trackIds[i]
  
  url <- paste0("https://itunes.apple.com/lookup?id=", song_id)
  response <- fromJSON(url)
  structured_response <- response$results
  
  return(tibble(structured_response))
})

saveRDS(itunes_data, "itunes_data.rds")

5.4 Data Visualisation

library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)

song_data = readRDS("song_data.rds") 

# Data Manipulation
explicitnessData = song_data %>%
  filter(trackExplicitness == "explicit") %>%
  group_by(rankedCountry) %>%
  summarise(noExplicit = length(trackExplicitness))

# Visualisation
explicitnessChart = ggplot(explicitnessData) +
  geom_col(aes(x = rankedCountry, y = noExplicit)) + 
  labs(title = "Number of Explicit Songs in Top 100 by Country",
       x = "Number of Explicit Songs",
       y = "Country",
       caption = "Source: Apple Music") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, 
                                  size = 12, 
                                  face = "plain", 
                                  margin = margin(t = 5, r = 5, b = 5, l = 5, unit = "pt")),
        plot.caption = element_text(hjust = 1,
                                    face = "italic",
                                    margin = margin(t = 5, r = 5, b = 5, l = 5, unit = "pt")),
        axis.title.x = element_text(margin = margin (t = 5)),
        axis.text.x = element_text(size = 7.5),
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white", colour = "black", size = 1),
        panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "grey", size = 0.075),
        panel.grid.minor = element_line(colour = "grey")) +
  ylim(0, 100)

ggsave("song_vis.png", 
       plot = explicitnessChart,
       width = 6, 
       height = 5, 
       units = "in")
